<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-03-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-03-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="215" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d215">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811b.01/63</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the Committee on Insular Affairs of
                                the House of Representatives</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Fairfield</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-03-25"><hi rend="italic">March 25,
                                1924</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Sir</hi>: The Insular Affairs Committee of the
                            House of Representatives has directed me to inquire of the State
                            Department as to whether the granting of Independence at this time to
                            the <pb facs="0379" n="265" xml:id="pg_265"/> Philippine Islands would
                            be contrary to any provisions of the Four Power Pact.<note n="51" xml:id="d215fn51"><ref target="frus1922v01#pg_33"><hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1922, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 33</ref>.</note></p>
                        <p>An early reply would be very much appreciated.</p>
                        <p>Very sincerely yours,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Louis W.
                            Fairfield</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>